{"type":"article","slug":"vir/content/21/3/515","journal":"vir","canonical":"https://www.sgmjournals.org/vir/content/21/3/515","meta":{"title":"The Replication of Polyoma DNA","authors":["Crawford, L. V.","Syrett, Christine","Wilde, Annelie"],"journalTitle":"Journal of General Virology","journalAbbrev":"","volume":"21","issue":"3","firstpage":"515","lastpage":"","date":"12/01/1973","doi":"10.1099/0022-1317-21-3-515","issn":[],"pmid":"4128636","mjid":"vir;21/3/515","section":"","abstractUrl":"http://vir.sgmjournals.org/cgi/content/abstract/21/3/515","fulltextUrl":"","pdfUrl":"http://vir.sgmjournals.org/cgi/reprint/21/3/515.pdf","publicUrl":""},"abstractHtml":"<p>Measurement of replicating molecules of polyoma virus DNA after digestion with endonuclease R<sub>1</sub> shows that DNA replication is bidirectional, starting predominantly at a specific site. In both large plaque and small plaque polyoma virus DNA this site is 29 ± 2% of the total length of the DNA from the cleavage site of the endonuclease R<sub>1</sub>.</p>","bodyHtml":"","referencesHtml":"","affiliationsHtml":"","correspHtml":"","pdfPath":null,"summaryHtml":"","ccTier":"tier3-abstract","refdomains":0}